.keyboard-shortcuts th:first-child {
    text-align: center;
}

.keyboard-shortcuts td:first-child {
    text-align: right;
}

    .keyboard-shortcuts th.keyboard-shortcut-section {
        background: hsl(268.46deg 45.95% 47.7% / 14%);
        text-align: left;
        border-radius: 0.5rem;
    }
View this list in PlutoPress F1 or ? in Pluto to see a pop-up with the most important tips.
Additionally, Pluto supports handy multi-select features: press Tab for multiple cursors, or hold  to make clean rectangular selections.Navigating between cellsYou can navigate between cell inputs using the arrow keys: when your cursor is at the beginning or end of a cell, you can use additional arrow key presses to navigate to the next or previous cell.You can also use fn‚Üë and fn‚Üì (on Mac) or Page Up and Page Down to jump between cells directly.Keyboard-only navigationPluto can be used in keyboard-only mode, using tabbing navigation. Use Tab to move focus to the next element. Inside the code editor press Esc first, then Tab, because Tab alone indents your code. Use ShiftTab to move focus back.Keyboard-only navigation is important for accessibility, so if you find a UI element that has poor keyboard access, please let us know!
const isMac = /Mac/i.test(navigator.userAgentData?.platform ?? navigator.platform);
const controlName = isMac ? "‚åÉ" : "Ctrl"; // ‚åÉ
const ctrlOrCmd = isMac ? "‚åò" : "Ctrl";  // ‚åò
const altName = isMac ? "‚å•" : "Alt";     // ‚å•
const and = isMac ? " " : "+";
const foldPrefix = isMac ? `${altName}${and}${ctrlOrCmd}` : `Ctrl${and}Shift`;
for (const el of document.querySelectorAll('.control-name')) el.textContent = controlName;
for (const el of document.querySelectorAll('.ctrl-or-cmd')) el.textContent = ctrlOrCmd;
for (const el of document.querySelectorAll('.alt-name')) el.textContent = altName;
for (const el of document.querySelectorAll('.and')) el.textContent = and;
for (const el of document.querySelectorAll('.fold-prefix')) el.textContent = foldPrefix;

Markdown in PlutoMarkdown is the easiest way to write text in Pluto notebooks. With Markdown, you can write text with bold, italic, and other formatting, and you can use it to add titles, lists, images, and more.You use markdown with the md""" string macro inside a Pluto cell:md"""
This text is in **bold** and _italic_.
"""
This is what that looks like in the notebook:Complete guideRead more about Markdown in Pluto here:Loading...How use Markdown in Pluto ‚Üí
